  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Once a property settles, most sellers move on quickly. The campaign is over, the funds have cleared, the next chapter is starting. The reflection on what worked, what did not, and what they would do differently next time is a step that almost no seller takes formally. Across hundreds of Brisbane sales, however, the same regrets surface in conversation again and again. They are not random; they are systematic, and they are almost always avoidable with better preparation.</p>

      <p>This article distils the ten regrets that come up most often from Brisbane sellers in the months and years after settlement. The pattern is the same whether the property was a $850,000 starter home in Coorparoo or a $2.4m family home in Hawthorne. Knowing the pattern in advance is the cheapest way to avoid it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 1: Choosing the agent on commission rate alone</h2>
      <p>The cheapest agent on the listing presentation often produces a lower net result than a moderately more expensive but better agent. The commission saving is typically a few thousand dollars; the price difference between a well-run and poorly-run campaign on a typical inner-east property is regularly twenty to one hundred thousand dollars or more. The lesson is that the agent decision should be made on track record (recent comparable sales they have actually closed), strategy (specifically how they would market and price your property), negotiation skills (how they handle offers and create competitive tension), and the quality of the proposed campaign, not on commission rate. A half per cent saved on commission disappears immediately if it costs you a serious buyer in negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 2: Overpricing the initial asking price</h2>
      <p>The most common pricing mistake is starting too high in the hope of capturing an aspirational buyer or leaving room to negotiate down. The actual outcome is the opposite: high initial prices attract few inquiries, give the listing stale-day stigma as it sits on portals, and force later price reductions that signal weakness to the buyer pool. Once a property has been on market for six to eight weeks at a price that has not produced offers, every subsequent buyer assumes there is something wrong with it. The lesson is to price realistically from week one based on comparable sales evidence in your suburb, in your price band, and in the last three to six months. Aspirational pricing is one of the most expensive mistakes sellers regret.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 3: Under-investing in pre-sale presentation</h2>
      <p>Minor cosmetic improvements (paint touch-up, decluttering, small repairs, garden tidy, professional cleaning, basic styling) typically pay back many times over in buyer perception and price. The total cost is usually one to three thousand dollars. Many sellers skip this work to save the money, then take a five to twenty thousand dollar discount in negotiation because the property presents tired. The lesson is to invest roughly half to one and a half per cent of expected sale price in pre-sale presentation. Spend it on the items the agent specifically recommends after walking the property, not on speculative improvements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 4: Refusing the first acceptable offer</h2>
      <p>First offers are often the strongest of the campaign, because the buyer who acts decisively in the first week or two is usually the most motivated, has done the most homework, and is willing to pay above the casual buyer. Sellers regularly refuse the first acceptable offer in the belief that a higher one is coming, then watch the campaign drift through weeks four, five, and six with progressively lower offers. The lesson is to evaluate offers against the market evidence (comparable sales, current buyer pool depth, agent feedback) rather than against an emotional anchor or a hopeful expectation. If the first offer is at or above realistic market value with strong terms, accept it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 5: Not understanding the campaign timeline</h2>
      <p>The first two to three weeks of a campaign capture the most serious buyers. After week four, the buyer pool weakens because the most engaged buyers have either offered or moved on. After week six to eight, the listing carries stale-day stigma and the remaining buyers assume the seller is under pressure. The lesson is to make the first weeks count with proper preparation: photography ready, marketing copy strong, open home schedule confirmed, agent briefed, contract pack prepared. Sellers who launch with the campaign half-ready waste the most valuable two weeks of buyer attention they will get.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 6: Disclosing too little or too late</h2>
      <p>Buyers find issues with the property regardless of whether the seller discloses them, through building and pest inspections, council searches, and conversations with neighbours. Late discovery destroys trust and gives the buyer leverage in negotiation. Up-front disclosure builds trust, gives the buyer the information they need to make a decision without surprise, and removes the negotiation lever. The lesson is to use a pre-listing disclosure checklist to identify and document everything material: known structural issues, pest history, drainage or flooding events, neighbour disputes, body corporate matters, council notices, easements and encumbrances. Get ahead of the issues that will surface anyway.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 7: Not preparing for the post-settlement transition</h2>
      <p>The administrative side of moving (utility transitions, address changes with banks and government, removalist booking, mail redirection, school enrolment changes if relocating, vehicle and licence updates) is mundane but consequential when left to the last minute. Sellers regularly arrive at settlement with these items half-complete and spend the following weeks chasing missed accounts, redirecting mail that has gone to the old address, and managing small financial losses from late cancellations. The lesson is to start the moving and transition checklist eight weeks before settlement, not eight days. The administrative work itself is small; the cost of doing it under pressure on the morning of the move is meaningful.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 8: Over-renovating before listing</h2>
      <p>The temptation to renovate the kitchen, bathrooms, or both before listing in the hope of capturing premium price is one of the most expensive mistakes Brisbane sellers make. A forty to eighty thousand dollar kitchen renovation on a property targeting a one million dollar sale price rarely returns the spend; the buyer's mental model is that a new kitchen is expected at that price, not a premium feature. The lesson is to refresh rather than renovate unless you can clearly model the return based on comparable sales evidence. Painting cabinetry, replacing tapware, updating handles, and refreshing splashback grout typically produces a stronger return per dollar than a full renovation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 9: Going to auction without the right buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Auctions need at least three serious bidders to produce competitive tension and a strong result. With only one or two genuine bidders, an auction passes in or sells under reserve, and the property carries the post-auction stigma into the negotiation phase. The lesson is to let the buyer pool determine the method of sale, rather than choosing auction by default. Properties with broad family buyer appeal in active markets typically auction well. Properties with niche buyer appeal, in softer markets, or with characteristics that limit the buyer pool (specific layouts, unusual features, small unit blocks) often produce better outcomes through private treaty with a clear price guide.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Regret 10: Choosing the wrong settlement date</h2>
      <p>Settlement timing seems like a minor detail when negotiating a contract, but the wrong settlement date produces real costs. Long settlements (90 to 120 days) expose sellers to additional risks (buyer finance changes, market movement, the buyer's circumstances changing) and to the cost of holding the property longer than planned. Short settlements (14 to 21 days) may pressure buyers and reduce the price flexibility a seller could otherwise extract from a longer settlement window. Settlements that fall in awkward windows (the week before Christmas, mid-Easter, the day after Anzac Day) can complicate the conveyancing pipeline and the practical move. The lesson is to match settlement timing to genuine convenience for both parties, with awareness of the broader calendar.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What differentiates the best-managed sales</h2>
      <p>The sellers who avoid most of the regrets above tend to share a small set of habits. They are honest in their self-assessment about the property's strengths and weaknesses, rather than over-claiming on quality and presentation. They invest in preparation rather than chasing a higher asking price, on the basis that buyers respond to what they see and not to what the seller asserts. They trust the right agent's judgement on strategy, pricing, and negotiation, while still verifying the basis for the recommendations they receive. They respect the buyer's process and timing, treating buyer feedback as data rather than as something to argue with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Before listing, walk through the ten regrets above and identify the two or three you are most likely to have based on your specific situation. Address those proactively: get a second view on agent shortlist if commission rate is dominating your decision, run the pricing decision against three to five recent comparable sales rather than against a hopeful number, build the pre-sale presentation budget into the campaign plan from week one, brief your agent on how you want to handle first offers before they arrive, build the disclosure documentation pack before the listing goes live, start the moving checklist eight weeks before settlement, model the renovation question against actual comparable sales evidence rather than against an aspirational result, choose method of sale on buyer pool depth not on default preference, and set settlement timing on the basis of genuine convenience. You cannot eliminate all regret from a sale, but you can avoid the most common and the most expensive mistakes.</p>

